    Iframe: "https://www.youtube.com/embed/sBoKqNsxSsk",
    content: <>In programming terms, we usually call text a string. When you think of a string as a collection of letters, the term makes sense. All the letters, numbers, and symbols could be a string. For that matter, your name could be a string, and so could your address. In fact, the first Python program we used a string: “Hello World.”<br />Strings are only in quotes that quotes may be double quotes (" ") or single quotes (' ')<PrismCode code={`a = "Hello world"\nprint(a)\nprint(type(a)`} language="python" /><br />You can write the variable name and a string seperating with a equal to sign (=) <p></p><h5>Concatenating string</h5>if you want to concatanate ( adding two or more strings ) a and b variable as follows : <PrismCode code={`a = 'Strings in'\nb = 'Python'\nprint(a + b)`} language="python" /><h5>Embedding Strings</h5>To embed the string we use placeholders that is %s<PrismCode code={`a = "I have Scored"\nb = "1000 points"\n\nprint("I have Scored %s" % b) # %s is use to embed strings`} language="python" /><br />We can't take calculation like subtraction, division of strings<h5>Source Code</h5><PrismCode code={`a = "this is the tutorial of strings"\nprint(a)\nprint(len(a)) # len function is used to find the lenght of the strings alongwith spaces\nprint(a[1]) # square brackets is used to find the word in the 1 number (index is start with 0)\n\nprint(a * 100) # prints a variable 100 times\na = "this is the tutorial of \\n strings" # \\n is used to make a new line\na = "hello"\nb = "world" \nprint(a + b) # concatanate variable a and b\n\na = "I have Scored"\nb = "1000 points"\nprint("I have Scored %s" % b) # %s is use to embed strings`} language="python" /></>
